Date: 2026-02-10
Issue: Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols not rendering in Zen browser (Flatpak)
Symptom: Characters like 𝘾𝙊𝙉𝙁𝙀𝙎𝙎 (Mathematical Sans-Serif Bold Italic, U+1D400-U+1D7FF) displayed as boxes/tofu

========== ROOT CAUSE ==========

Custom ~/.config/fontconfig/fonts.conf only declared <dir>~/.local/share/fonts</dir>,
causing Zen to ignore the Flatpak runtime's bundled fonts at /usr/share/fonts/.

This fontconfig was intentionally created to fix CJK font priority (Chinese fonts
rendering instead of Japanese). It replaced the default fontconfig entirely, which
had the side effect of hiding all runtime-bundled fonts.

Note: the Flatpak "Path /usr is reserved" warning is about the HOST's /usr — the
runtime's internal /usr/share/fonts is accessible and is NOT blocked by Flatpak.

========== TRIALS ==========

1. Copy math fonts to user directory → WORKED (but not root cause fix)

   What:
     $ cp /usr/share/fonts/google-noto/NotoSansMath-Regular.ttf ~/.local/share/fonts/
     $ cp -r /usr/share/fonts/stix-fonts/ ~/.local/share/fonts/stix-fonts
     $ fc-cache -fv ~/.local/share/fonts

   Why worked:
     ~/.local/share/fonts/ was the only <dir> in the custom fontconfig,
     so fonts placed here are always visible. Both NotoSansMath and
     STIXTwoMath contain Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols (confirmed
     via fontTools cmap check).

2. Add runtime font dir to custom fontconfig → SUCCESS (root cause fix)

   What:
     Added <dir>/usr/share/fonts</dir> to ~/.config/fontconfig/fonts.conf

   Why worked:
     The runtime (org.freedesktop.Platform) bundles DejaVu, Liberation,
     Noto Emoji, TeX Gyre, etc. at /usr/share/fonts INSIDE the sandbox.
     Adding this dir makes all runtime fonts visible again.

   Why safe:
     Runtime does not include any CJK fonts, so the Japanese font
     priority fix is not affected.

========== TAKEAWAY ==========

- FONTCONFIG_FILE override replaces ALL default fontconfig behavior.
  Any custom fonts.conf must explicitly list every font directory.
- Flatpak's "/usr is reserved" only applies to the HOST's /usr.
  The runtime's internal /usr/share/fonts is always accessible.
- When debugging Flatpak font issues, check FONTCONFIG_FILE first —
  a custom fontconfig hiding font dirs is more likely than a sandbox issue.

Actual fix: ./2026-02-10-flatpak-fontconfig-fix.log
